A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that voter fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Moreover, Republican lawyers have identified only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will undermine some of the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require voters to present photo identification and proof of U.S. citizenship.
These laws also reduce advance polling periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on election day, and strip citizens with a criminal record of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present photo identification.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
For the past two years, they were sponsoring bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens, or 21 million voting-age people, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, voters seen as voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their institution-issued photo ID.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
Separately, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on Election Day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed legislation in five other states aimed at reducing the advance polling period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33 percent of electors who voted in advance polls were African-American, while they represented only 13 percent of voters in the state.
It was the same with Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, whites who made up 76% of voters represented only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters vigorously opposed passing laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes by Democratic governors.
The U.S. attorney general intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit some of the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of photo identification.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious objective to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes the Electoral College needs to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures will undermine some of the American democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: get tested or not?
Indeed, the PSA test would sometimes have erroneous results, with false negative results or false positives, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
Enough to make men already reluctant to take screening tests hesitate even more.
To take the test or not?
We sought the advice of two experts.
In the studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, this one from Europe, found a difference in mortality between patients who were screened and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that we are between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if we are not detected.
I therefore recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
There is a real need to make the patient understand the degree of risk of their cancer, by giving them the options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not interfere with long-term life, and by opting instead, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are found to have cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and not life-threatening.
We will suggest that they do active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we will offer them treatment.
Increasingly, criteria are being determined precisely to decide who should or should not be treated.
So I still recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine if you should have it or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool to assess the pros and cons of PSA testing.
The document can be downloaded (in English for the time being, a translation will be available shortly) at: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle recipe for preventing cancer.
Despite advances in research, adopting good lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risk of suffering from it.
It is estimated that if everyone ate well and moved enough, 30% of cancers could be prevented.
"If no one smoked anymore, this rate would rise to at least 50%," says André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
On the other hand, it is estimated that about 10% of cancers are caused by heredity.
Many also remain totally unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, tobacco control remains a priority, despite the decrease in the number of smokers.
Smoking is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for many others.
It is very detrimental to people's health.
"Even today, there are 1.5 million smokers in Quebec," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouragingly, 10 years after quitting, the risk of dying from cancer drops by half.
Weight
Being overweight and obese also contribute to the onset of the disease, according to the CCS.
They would increase the risk of cancer of the breast, colon and rectum, esophagus, pancreas and uterus.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout a lifetime protects against colon cancer," it adds.
Food
The organization also recommends limiting your consumption of red meat.
In too large quantities, it increases the risk of developing colorectal cancer.
Cold cuts too, and they should be avoided.
Preserving meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogenic substances.
"These can damage the body's cells and lead to the development of cancer," it explains.
Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin supplements and cancer.
However, their research is not conclusive at this time.
Studies on vitamin E are contradictory, according to the CCS.
While one of them noted a decrease in the risk of prostate cancer, another noted an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer is also unclear.
In addition, Mr. Beaulieu emphasizes the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
"Getting tested doesn't give cancer."
The dissected Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, no less.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model – our best, or "least worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter – but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is indeed the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain.
Let's assume that it is indeed the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this world, a fatally inescapable law according to which two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
But even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least, not for this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, Berkeley Laboratories: mesons, which we will not discuss here, and "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all critters as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this column, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in that precise place, a bit like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; To excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a bit like a frozen pond where only a very large rock could wrinkle the surface.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't – a piece of paper, for example, will never stand on its own on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, hold on) do not.
Now, what "can all this research bring" asks, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and MS predictions.
Many of them fervently wish that we find them, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter in the Universe (re-oops!).
But no such discrepancies have been found at CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of this research on the daily lives of ordinary people is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
Look: at the very beginning of the 60s, the pioneers of the laser, in Bell Laboratories, had no idea of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 – once told us that the laser was seen more as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative Care - The Best Way to Die... | The Duty
With its Dying with Dignity Commission, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
Debate is expected to resume shortly as a bill prepares.
However, in this crucial area, much remains to be done.
Le Devoir tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating away at him had given him a two-year respite.
"They gave me five years to live, I did seven years," he says, half-fig half-grape, lying in bed at the Victor Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even from eating alone.
Seated in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers around him, brings him his medicine, offers him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is for me to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
"During our lives, we learn that a man pisses standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Maison Victor-Gadbois.
Regressing to the stage of the child, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept regression, he says.
Because, in the opinion of many people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor Gadbois Palliative Care Home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life prognosis of three months.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life anymore," she says, before agreeing to be put on a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting, in the coming days, for a last visit from her son from Italy.
At Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provides body care and food assistance.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little when you know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the house's doctors.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person will be willing to provide mouth care with brandy or Pepsi, depending on demand.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, Mr. X, who died during the night, was served a beer.
This morning, it is his son who will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At Maison Victor-Gadbois, the days follow one another but are not alike.
Alongside a 93-year-old man enjoying his last family gathering in the courtyard, propped up in his pillows while toasting in his honour, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to Maison Victor-Gadbois arrive from home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as Maison Victor-Gadbois and the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this major deficiency in Quebec health care that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care luminaries including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health care system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will have the right to quality palliative care before euthanasia is agreed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without being done to relieve her.
I am concerned that patients will only ask to die because they are not receiving proper care.
And at the same time, many oncologists are persecuting their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's hopes of survival were already minimal when she abandoned a gruelling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she said she regretted that I stopped fighting," she said.
Still, she told me I was finished!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not acceding to their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Palliative Home Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to putting the patient to sleep until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
More and more, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me," it means "I want relief."
