Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Road officials, construction contractors, political party fundraisers and Italian mafia specialists tell day after day what they know about a formidable "system", mixing construction industry, civil servants, politicians, trade unionists and mafioso.
An "industry" that cost Quebec taxpayers dearly, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's curious how the system has crumbled since we took the big means," said Jacques Duchesneau, MP for Quebec City and former police chief of Montreal.
It was through him that the scandal broke in 2011, through a thorough investigation into embezzlement related to road work contracts in Quebec, to which the Liberal premier at the time, Jean Charest, had only consented backwards.
The "Duchesneau Report" established a direct link between industry, hidden party financing and corruption of public officials.
"Since the beginning of the investigation in 2010, he points out, the Ministry of Transport alone would have saved a billion dollars on contracts", some restraining their instincts to receive a share!
The Charbonneau Commission "has already brought down two mayors," he adds, hoping that it will succeed in "demonstrating the stratagems behind individuals."
A permanent anti-corruption unit, created in 2011
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, created in 2011, is also working on this with its army of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
Plus the police officers of the "hammer squad" who, since 2009, would have led the "sewer cartel" of Montreal to put the pedal soft on the inflating contracts...
In recent weeks, it has conducted serial raids and brought charges of fraud and corruption against elected officials, such as Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, mayor of a suburban city.
Next on the list would be Gilles Vaillancourt, who has just resigned as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of having pocketed repeated bribes in exchange for public contracts.
Montreal road engineers and Italian-born contractors, including Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, are also formally charged.
The latter caused a sensation by explaining to the commission the mechanics of the "system" of obtaining public contracts.
He himself paid for years 3% of the value of the contracts obtained in Montreal to an intermediary linked to the mafia who paid the money to Union Montreal, the party of Mayor Gérald Tremblay.
Mr. Zambito sowed all winds in the 2000s, giving more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to provincial parties, especially to the Liberals then in power.
He also admitted to organizing an illegal fundraiser for former Liberal deputy premier Nathalie Normandeau.
Sewer contracts whose costs he inflated
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption was working smoothly.
Gilles Surprenant, a former public works engineer, detailed it well before the commission: in ten years, he received from construction companies gifts, invitations to trips, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey games and bribes totaling $ 736,000, in exchange for sewer contracts whose costs he inflated.
Other road officials have confessed to having been greased by inflating bills by 30% to 40%, by false extras.
Then an organizer of the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr. Tremblay of deliberately turning a blind eye to a parallel budget feeding his coffers with dirty money.
Following these revelations, Mr. Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a major crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first elected officials in Montreal to sound the alarm.
Mayor of the borough of Rivière-des-Prairies, east of the island, she rebelled in 2010 against the sale of municipal land bought $ 5 million and resold... 1.6 million to developers, in the midst of a real estate boom.
70% dirty money in election campaigns
Of the investigation that will finally be set up, she says she is "pulling on a thread to understand the functioning of the system, infiltrated by ants, to stop gangrene and pin the culprits".
The process, she says, is "painful but positive."
We are cleaning up the wound, but we need a specific investigation unit in Montreal and a watch, so as not to see the return of questionable practices.
As we clean up.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau notes for his part that "civil servants have stolen hundreds of millions of dollars", but is especially worried about the role of "elected officials aware of the stratagem", when they did not dip into the scheme!
Estimating at 70% the share of dirty money in the financing of electoral campaigns in Quebec, he jokes: "I was told that it was only a pale reflection of reality."
The Quebec government proposes to limit donations to parties to $ 100 but this will not change the situation, according to him: "As long as we do not strictly limit election spending, there will be dirty money in politics."
He advocates a complete overhaul of the system for awarding public contracts and party financing: "We cannot go any lower; Getting to the bottom of things, with courage, will allow us to rebuild the house on a firmer foundation, with more controls and laws."
If this story tarnishes the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau invites those who laugh at it to look in their own backyard...
