With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
Quite the opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as is often the case in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files peer-to-peer.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars five months later, before returning today around ten dollars (prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com site).
Nothing very impressive, compared to global exchanges in real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or euro," and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to progress in a video game that you win by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both custodians of the ledger, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two email addresses like an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged exist in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, whose winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hashing phase, which is the transformation of a large file into a shorter, unique digital fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "chopping" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the correct one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; Any changes would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this award is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves room for ...
The difficulty of the challenge is also met with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
"The flaw used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on money laundering opportunities through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Major players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the account book and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant sales" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged," said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement at merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
In its report, the ECB also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans should follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain its territory and for Afghans to choose their future, without expecting everything from us.
It is mainly the Afghan peasants whom we have punished by considering them terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former leaders who have taken refuge in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in Soviet times.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes helped by local insurgents, they will no longer be when Westerners are more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the top of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was done in order.
Convoys of trucks and armoured vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, overflown by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban surge into Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country on fire and blood because of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overwhelmed by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved today.
Former mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban come together in the desire to keep women in an inferior position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land and selling it as building land to refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge US subcontracts.
They have discredited themselves; Most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have benefited from American largesse: capital flight is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They have rubbed shoulders with the modern world during their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they have appreciated its advantages.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has a population of 5 million, one-fifth of the total population.
In the cities, government schools are full of girls and boys alike.
It will be necessary to provide work for these young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or the corruption of certain leaders.
Everyone, including armed opponents, is fond of mobile phones; Television, and its Turkish soap operas that present a modern world, is followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who will order it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already preoccupied with reconstituting provincial militias, which will escape the central power.
Afghanistan, a country of mountains, with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from a certain decentralization, like Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, abolishing the post of Prime Minister that had existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially in the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country is, since the 50s and already well before, dependent on foreign aid.
No industry has been restarted, no dams are in repair, no major irrigation system has been repaired.
Everything is imported; Nothing is produced, except fruits and vegetables.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country ruined by thirty years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
There were rumours that Afghanistan possessed immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that Westerners were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process iron or copper ore locally, or transportation to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the huge Buddhist site and remain the province's largest employers.
Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports largely depend, will also have to re-establish normal relations one day.
The departure of the French fighting troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aid: girls' and boys' high school, French department at university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and achieve the impossible task of matching aid and offensive actions, a "civil-military actions" service of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has carried out, and had a small French NGO carry out, many works of collective interest and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, which require local labour, were able to help contain the insurgency: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and an increase in arable land.
What will we leave as a memory, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys often located at more than 2,000 meters above sea level.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which I have told farmers want, they should have a small amount of civilian aid, well controlled and which affects them directly.
A forceps constitution in Egypt
This is a new poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants him full powers, he has decided to play his part.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this Assembly two more months to finish its work.
For almost two years, Egypt has relied on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only widened the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample on the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end as quickly as possible the institutional and political crisis, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within two weeks.
A very short period of time that forced the Brothers to abandon their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while protests rage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep full powers", which supposedly have to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted for the text yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done likewise.
In order to ensure that the necessary quorum was reached, 11 people, alternate members, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted.
Commentators were also amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around ... The time of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the pendulum of the constituent assembly was badly regulated.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Object of all attention, Article 2 ultimately remains identical to that of the Constitution of 1971, stipulating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," say the liberals, who see it as only a publicity stunt.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to vote are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see in it the beginnings of a theocracy."
Liberal fears are further fuelled by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil registry.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema but academics, some of whom were trained in the French system," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on Egypt's constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, editor's note].
And the question may arise in the future as to what extent civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts, as requested by human rights groups, be banned.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider repressive.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly of the press.
Moreover, no article more echoes the protection of women, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy sites, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comforts and wilderness.
Argoumenty i Fakty has identified five main reasons for you to visit Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
A must-see event: the banks of the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever enters these "baptismal funds" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of Jesus' miracles: where water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on water, where he calmed the storm or where fishing was miraculous.
It was here that Jesus appeared before His disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Street of Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia fortress (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, and then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the Entombment.
It is here that the Christian center of the world is located, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is erected on the spot where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for Jews: the Western Wall which is the remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small notes accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel high up
Visit the ruins of the Masada Fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC. for his family.
These ruins lie on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can get there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle bus can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs have it that pagan gods once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are definitely worth seeing.
First: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very ancient Qumran Scrolls, or Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the paintings of the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which looks back at the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter into total darkness.
Stars twinkle.
You then hear the names of Jewish children and the names of countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major resorts lie on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the water temperature does not drop below 21 ° while that of the air can reach 23 °.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, this is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, which is 417 m below sea level.
The azure-colored water contains brine and very easily holds bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
People come here to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, healing mud and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by Tel Aviv's Old City, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived here a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow alleys that are named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who come to do photo shoots from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable into shekels (today 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The ride on all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants, and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales, and dishes consisting of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish paste, different sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats who walk around looking haughty.
They can be seen sleeping on the roofs of parked cars in the evening.
These felines love places passing by and do not refuse to be feasted.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 per day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who language has, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists debate what the mandatory language test law will do, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families back home.
Since 1 December, a law has entered into force stipulating that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian language test.
At this time, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the service, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the History of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will have to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has the status of an official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained teaching certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders had already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it look like?
What will the requirement to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, say the representatives of the migration service, it will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says Victor Sebelev, director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without the understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the would-be migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" to an overcrowded cottage where he and dozens of his ilk will torment themselves for months without food and papers and will have to toil between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, they are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, their passports are taken, and they do not receive the expected salary," confirms the head of the Directorate of Migration Services for Labour of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't argue with me, Mr. Policeman!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to come and earn money in Russia confide that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to visit, but also that they have difficulty writing in their own language.
This is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children let alone dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's difficult when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights advocates, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be for migrants who have legal status only.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbid to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
And then one can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, enough to buy cigarettes, tea," Umed Khushkadamov, a national of Tajikistan, told reporters.
"Hurry, don't skimp and buy yourself a beautiful work of art"
From the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it was discovered that it was not only the migrants' registration papers that were fake.
Several fake language exam certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Forged papers come out of a regular colour printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: each migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of the examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Officials and human rights advocates agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "pieces of paper".
The authorities can give migrant workers who were unable to pass the exam the first time to attend language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in fields that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs is proposing to toughen the law against civilian weapon bearers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: from the shooting at weddings to the killing of Moscow jurist Dmitry Vinogradov, which left seven people dead.
The police want to ban the carrying of rubber guns in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a gun permit from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the weapons law would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter has appeared on the Internet in which its authors, representatives of various firing centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police department while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that strengthening civilian gun laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, today you can find in Moscow any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for weapons is supplied through several channels.
There are five main canals, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot from a site taking orders for weapons
The first is the "military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these include weapons stolen from police stocks as well as weapons stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of the latter have often suffered explosions.
"Documented versions indicate that some fires were deliberately started to cover up the deficit," says the former soldier.
For Baranets, arms manufacturers have something to do with it.
"We see private arms factories that do not compete with the competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," says an expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former soldier.
Where do the weapons come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the guns on the black market ended up there "through the fault of employees whose work is related to the weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% come from "clandestine excavations".
A salesman and consultant at an armory who asked to remain anonymous said that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these clandestine search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, he said, vendors pick up new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, for example a TT pistol.
It is delivered to him by passing the goods through a fence.
"He transports it to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a control purchase from illegal arms dealers," the seller added.
" Like in a luxury boutique "
The seller and buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted sites, blogs, until a guy came forward and offered me to come to the Begovaya station where someone became taking me to a "corner" to haggle.
The price of the gun, I was given it on the spot
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I don't trust them.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you also have to come and say, for example, "From such and such a person, who asked me to pass on that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only delivers them to me because he knows I won't give them away.
Newcomers are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former soldier Victor Baranets tried his hand as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, he said, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything you want".
"I thought I was in a luxury boutique," recalls the soldier.
There is no secret for the buyer, explains Baranets, you can try everything.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller in the forest and we install a target.
"They let me shoot and when I am convinced that the weapon works well, we start negotiating," the expert describes.
A shop from his sofa
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where one can buy weapons "for different uses".
For this, we do not need any documents and no one to meet.
"It is enough to have a precise amount of money," one writes in advertising on the site "Buy a pistol or a combat submachine gun".
Users leave their request and ask their questions.
And we sell to miners?
"Without a license, of course," asks the user "Ivan" (spelling retained).
"Buy TT. Moscow," writes "Fedorenkov" in his very direct request.
The Federal Security Service has disseminated a huge network of fake sites and picks up people who want to buy combat weapons in spades.
