United States: Fast-food and supermarket workers on strike
Nearly a quarter of U.S. teens go through a job as a cashier at McDonald's
In recent days, a wave of protests has mounted against low wages practiced by Walmart supermarkets and famous fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
At the moment, no one can predict whether this wave will grow or run out of steam quickly.
These actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing associations.
Along with the increase in the modest wages received by rank-and-file workers at Walmart and fast food chains, the organizers of the protests are seeking the creation of unions.
This sector is not currently covered by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week, after Thanksgiving, the "Black Friday", when a rain of sales seizing millions of inhabitants fell on America and sometimes triggering esclanders.
On that day, some workers at Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, quit their jobs to organize pickets with unions and left-wing activists in the company's stores whose products are aimed at low- and middle-class consumers.
Walmart markets everything from diapers and shotguns to car batteries, vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That's why many low-paid Walmart employees shop only at their workplace.
The price and choice of products have made Walmart one of the most powerful groups in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell its products cheaply in part because of the low wages of its employees.
They also complain about difficult working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or hand-held scanners.
Participants in the "Black Friday" protests were demanding a pay raise, complaining that the price of medical insurance provided by the company had increased from $30 to $100 per month.
For the basic Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour, that's a sum he can't afford.
Scientists at the University of California, Berkley show that if Walmart raised the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost the group $3.2 billion.
That's 1.1% more than he currently spends.
If Walmart shifted all the wage increases onto consumers' shoulders, each ride in the store would cost them 46 cents more.
They will spend in a year only $12.39 more than they do now.
Walmart supporters note with satisfaction that the protests took place in only nine states and did no harm to the group.
"Black Friday" continued in stores from 8 p.m. to midnight the next day, and Walmart sold 5,000 items per second over that period.
Its cash registers made a total of 100 million transactions for "Black Friday".
Company spokesman Dan Fogleman said in an interview with the left-leaning Huffington Post that "fewer than five" Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest was just one "communication operation among many" by the organizing union.
"Next customer!"
The protests continued this week in New York and were no longer about Walmart stores (in this progressive city, they are not very popular, which is why they are not yet established there) but McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's advertises selling billions of servings and then they don't even give you sick leave and don't pay you for the work you did honestly!
Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York legislation is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food restaurants increase them over time, but by a small margin, on average its basic employees in New York earn $8.90 an hour.
No one gets less than them in this city.
For me it is inconceivable to live with this sum in New York.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers worked at McDonald's after high school while living with their parents.
Few people saw it as their main source of income or wanted to stay there for a long time.
Today, I find myself interviewing McDonald's employees who complain about having to live on that salary and sometimes having to feed their children with it.
On the other hand, on the Wall Street Journal forum there are comments saying that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know what you are going to feed them with.
The protesters who launched the movement Thursday at 6:30 a.m. near McDonald's on 40th Street and on Madison Avenue demanded that cashiers and cooks at the fast-food restaurant be paid a minimum of $15 an hour, a more than double the current minimum wage.
They also called for the creation of unions in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from obstructing it and punishing union protesters with bullying or firing.
However, the administration rarely simplifies their lives.
For a union, taking over fast food remains a difficult task, and for concrete reasons.
One of the main ones is the extraordinary turnover of staff.
They disagree
Other tumultuous protests were held near several other fast food chains.
