The protesters were supported by other prominent New York Democrats, including mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio who said that "we must all support fast food workers to get the fair wage and economic well-being that every New Yorker deserves.
The New York Times characterized the event as the largest in the history of the fast food industry.
But only a few hundred people participated, not all of them were fast-food workers, which employ tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is currently difficult to say whether this spark of mass movement will make babies.
"At the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain"
Lately, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, it was Google that unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November we learned that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it appears from the interview with Shahram Izadi, director of the interactive 3D technologies group at the Microsoft Cambridge Lab, that for the company's scientists, glasses are already history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, by creating open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
Humanity as a whole has so far remained with pixels on flat screens and sometimes touch.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead of us and guess the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox today sells without Kinect because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What does the future hold?
- Although the Kinect has made the interaction physical, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information capture has been improved (the system receives more data), but performance at this time is not really important.
We're trying to change that and we're working on truly 3D imaging systems that work on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We have to bring the computer world out into ours, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the space around him.
Thus, we will be able to supplement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And for starters, let's get rid of those stupid VR headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It is appreciated, but is it not overrated?
We cannot say that this is a panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because we do not always want to inform others of our actions or intentions.
In fact, every type of interaction with the computer is good, but each in its niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discreet, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the device's camera, but by a hand-worn bracelet that recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by mixed control, for example: gesture + voice.
- That is?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can?
You would do it with words and actions.
- Usually, I'm just talking.
- Oh, it's going to be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt based on what the machine can or cannot do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on developing new types of sensors that will allow us to better identify human reactions.
It can be for example laser sensors, they produce a fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
- If we're interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don't you like about modern cameras?
They lack resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we base ourselves in our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be nice to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c/s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all current technologies are quite good, it adds work to algorithm designers.
We must keep in mind the resolution according to the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the 30 c/s is really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our Redmond lab, gave the touch of the sensors a regular processing delay of between 1 and 100 μs, with current sensors closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how much this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device of this type in my work, but not requiring touch, to have more frames per second.
- But shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- The Kinect today has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared emitter and the second, a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a usual visible field sensor.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
Many cameras could solve this problem...
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a soft product similar to the Kinect, play with the camera curve and see how it could help define locations.
- As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the platforms with the most perspectives?
- Of course, walking around all the time with a smartphone with your hands raised is not practical but here's what I think: the best option would be a "transient" augmented reality that would allow you from a cloud platform to switch from glasses to smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device and that's what makes them strong (personal elements are the ones you are the only one to see) and at the same time their weakness: augmented reality from glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is one problem that opponents of this idea point to : there is no tactile sensation!
The hands don't feel anything!
What responses is your group preparing in relation to this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could very well be the addition of tactile sensations.
At the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as an image support.
It records the pressures perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really intended to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example the interference of several ultrasound rays directed at a precise point where the finger is located and which gives you the sensation, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the tips of the fingers.
There are also bracelets worn on the wrists that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, they are also a line of work with perspectives.
- And you tried to fool the brain?
Make him believe that he feels what he should normally feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
There is still one task there that will have to be worked with for a long time: how to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that he is walking in an almost infinite open space - we are working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs),  mobile platforms and also giant balls.
For the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain, there are still many years of work.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
