Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Space shuttle caravans with earthlings on board go in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how to continue to support our species in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there is much choice.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, if only by hypothesis.
"These are Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500.
You can only live there at very high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Until half a century ago, experiments were carried out on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from terrestrial varieties.
Then we put into orbit insects, small reproductive fruit flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo developed.
At the exit, a completely normal chick is obtained.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find support, it has to get on its feet and start moving," says Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
Finding no support, the chicks were fidgeting in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophy.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We widened their eyes twice, then gave up, because it's just impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite "Bion" will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then this is the only experiment. This kind of research needs to be done," Sychev said.
After landing, space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to make reproductions directly in space.
This is no small feat.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instinct.
Unlike beasts, man is capable of it, in principle.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thinking, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been going into space for 50 years now.
The biggest risk was taken by Tereshkova.
And the feminine organism is the most precious thing humanity has.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold out after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the flight.
"No one was answering that question," says Vakhtang Vachnadze, a retired rocket and space worker.
In June 1964, just one year after her flight into space, the first female cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova gave birth to a baby girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after being in orbit twice and even working in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk remains.
We have few, if not very few, cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during orbit flights," concludes pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Polyakov.
Yet humanity must look for new solutions in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravitation.
Hydrology Laboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Center: mandatory stage of flight preparation.
Here, in zero buoyancy, cosmonauts train for spacewalks.
Water mimics weightlessness.
If for adults, water is comfortable but nevertheless a foreign environment, for infants, it is their true element.
The little amphibious men seem to confirm it: life on Earth originates from the ocean.
Since the baby evolves about 9 months in the lymphatic fluid of his mother's womb, it is easier for him to get used to the water afterwards.
This is in principle logical, because from birth to his first bath, only 2 weeks pass.
"It's very little to forget," says infant swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
In a word, if for the child who has just been born weightlessness is a more natural state, the woman needs gravitation, a force of weight.
In weightlessness, the muscles of the belly, pelvis atrophy very quickly, the baby's ability to push is lost.
Okay, let's ignore that by relying on birth simulators.
We can of course prepare a delivery in a special room, the woman will manage to get him out.
"What's next?" asks Valeriy Poliakov to invite reflection on this complex question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravitation.
If it does not feel the earthly attraction, the organism does not form the skeleton or the muscular system.
You can't dress an infant like an adult with a special suit for training.
He will simply be deprived of his vital needs.
"And this experiment that we would consider in this case imagining the birth of a child in a foreign environment will lead to the return to Earth of a disabled child, entirely maladapted," predicts the Director of the Committee for Bioethics of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
The birth of children in space is still a matter of theory.
However, in time this will become a reality, when Earthlings travel in their shuttles to a distant planet that will become the habitat of their space-born descendants.
The head of the SAI (Supreme Audit Institution) declared: "The control of pseudo self-employment (in Czech "Švarc system") has failed because of politicians.
In the area of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and high-quality legislation, but it lags behind in its implementation.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, the vice-president of the Supreme Audit Institution in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its enforcement must be fair and, in my opinion, this is what is lacking in us," Kala said in his commentary on the current situation.
A joint monitoring by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites Petr Nečas' "Švarc system" approach as an example of abusive practice.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS is not going to bother entrepreneurs with controls; So is this allowed or forbidden?
"The law has to be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority in charge of going to inspect to demand compliance with the law," Kala said.
At the meeting of the Control Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement legislation of these two countries was compared.
What was it about concretely?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and follows specific national legislation and practice itself.
We have put all this together, and although this control procedure has not yet been completed, some very interesting differences have arisen to us: generally speaking, our legislation may be 'stricter and of better quality', nevertheless, according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to continually develop more and more detailed rules, but that it is necessary to devote oneself to the actual implementation of the law.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it mean for you?
Joint monitoring of this kind should help us to stop trying to clarify laws, lower and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It could be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork, that those who look for loopholes will find many more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You talk about internal problems with the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different mode of organization?
As far as the institutions are concerned, like the SAI, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there, which is similarly organised, it also has a council constituted somewhat differently, but these two institutions basically proceed in a similar way.
The competences are also to some extent similar, albeit with one nuance compared to our system: Germany is a federal structure, so it also has courts of auditors of this type at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which in our country is the resources of the state.
The public funds managed here by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the courts of auditors of the Länder.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I do not want to make a general comparison without concrete data, but in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said to do better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better inspectors?
No, certainly not, but again, I do not have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we consider to be a model, is also facing a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they would have no advantage in cooperating with our institution, right?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has the amendment of the Public Procurement Act meant for you as an institution, are its effects already being felt?
As this amendment entered into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our control operations.
Since we carry out ex post controls, there is a certain delay.
Our observations concern only, for the moment, the process of preparing future controls - we have launched a new instrument for 'detecting risks of mismanagement' with which we have screened nearly 14 000 public contracts - there these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been changed as well as the conditions of certain types of tendering procedures and so on.
Do you therefore consider the adoption of this law more as an advantage or as an additional burden for the administration?
I believe that this legislation is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm that.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become stricter and it is not possible to comply with them.
Already under the previous regulations, the service provider (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the audited subjects to accept that any violation of the law on procurement meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really useful to make the law tougher in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system, but not punish those who make formal mistakes that have no impact on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS was not going to annoy entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called Švarc system - what does that mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or allowed?
The law has to be enforced in one way or another, so if it forbids something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going to inspect and demand compliance with the law.
He can say, "We are going to change the law and allow it," but he cannot say that we are going to act as if nothing had happened.
The law on contracts contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be completed, precisely in order to protect the invitation to tender.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied fairly, and I think that is what we are lacking.
The roads are frozen in places, but most remain passable.
In some parts of the Czech Republic, the roads are frozen and also snow-covered.
However, the network remains largely passable, in some places with increased vigilance.
Karlovy Vary Region
In the Karlovy Vary region, the roads were passable this morning, but in places frozen and also snow-covered.
Temperatures have dropped and are hovering between -5°C and -10°C but they are expected to rise slightly during the day.
Snowfall has stopped in the region and only a thin layer of snow remains on the plains.
The ridges of the Ore Mountains (Krušné hory) are, however, covered with about 30 centimetres of snow.
Data from the Regional Road Maintenance Service indicate that fog meant reduced visibility in some places.
The R6 expressway and the national roads in the region are now passable without difficulty.
However, vigilance is still required, for example on certain bridges whose surface can be frozen and slippery.
All county roads and third category roads, including mountain roads, are also passable.
On some of their sections, there are still remnants of frozen snow and in places packed by traffic.
Especially in high-altitude areas, drivers need to be extra vigilant.
Regions of Pardubice and Hradec Králové
The Directorate of Roads and Highways reports on its website that some roads in East Bohemia are threatened by ice and that layers of snow packed by traffic may be found on roads in mountainous and high-altitude areas.
Road maintenance services warn drivers of the risk of ice formation in high-altitude areas of the Pardubice region.
There may be ice in the vicinity of Lanškroun, Ústí nad Orlicí, Polička, Svitavy or Vysoké Mýto, mainly on county and third category roads.
The I/43 and I/34 roads around Svitavy were chemically treated.
Snow is mainly found in the Giant Mountains (Krkonoše) and the Eagle Mountains (Orlické hory).
In Rychnov nad Kněžnou and Trutnov districts, a layer of traffic-packed snow is present on roads in high-altitude areas.
In East Bohemia, the weather will now be dry, mostly clear, with possible cloudy passages.
It will blow a light wind and temperatures will usually oscillate between -3 ° and + 1 ° C.
Pilsen Region
The roads in the Pilsen region are now passable, although in places it is necessary to be more vigilant and to adapt one's driving to the weather conditions.
It freezes this morning, temperatures oscillate between -3 ° and -9 ° C.
After the last snowfall and the subsequent cooling, some communication routes may be frozen in places.
Drivers can expect to pass through areas of fog, but visibility will gradually improve.
This is what emerges from the information of the regional road maintenance service.
The D5 motorway is passable almost without difficulty, but the road communications maintenance services recommend increased vigilance between kilometres 80 and 131.
The pavement of most national roads is dry and frozen.
Some sections may be frozen in the South Pilsen district and the Tachov district.
The departmental and third category roads are wet and in this case the warning against frozen sections applies.
Drivers must be vigilant, especially on less busy roads in the Šumava region.
Olomouc Region
