Šimon Ornest said: "In concert, we want to collect positive energy."
What do you think of the fact that in less than a month it should be the end of the world?
This is just one of those alarming news, the kind of traps we like to fall into.
In our band The Tap Tap, we laugh about it and we say that we are the only band capable of collecting a remnant of positive energy in order to postpone or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you are putting together a very unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you present this project in more detail to our readers?
This is a charitable action that we have been preparing for two years now.
We decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 am.
The day before, on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously, in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end almost by the end of the Mayan calendar on the Pacific Ocean island of Kiribati, 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
At first I think it was my idea, then we designed everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.
Apart from the fact that we want to collect enough positive energy to save the world, we also want together, with the public, to reflect on the state of the world we leave to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have created a collection of unique objects, including shoes, T-shirts, bags, and original keys against the end of the world, by buying them online at www.e-tap.cz people can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap with other performers also recorded an anthem against the end of the world entitled " End of the World Cancelled " (in Czech " Konec světa zrušeno ").
It is already very popular on YouTube, will we also hear it at these charity concerts?
Of course, at the very end, finally, if we succeed and the end of the world does not take place...
It will be sung simultaneously by all performers in all three concerts.
The anthems will also come together at some point in a unique live broadcast on Czech television.
The lyrics of this song were written by Tomáš Hanák who also plays the main role of Jesus in the clip, Xindl X also sings there...
How did you come to cooperate with them?
We collaborate with other Czech showbiz personalities, due to the fact that we organize many concerts and charity events...
We strive to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in such cooperation and it amuses them.
What will the profits of these concerts against the end of the world be used for?
To equip the Studeo training center, which is accessible to people with reduced mobility and which we have been working on as part of the Jedlička Institute, with the Tap association, and this for six years.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedličkův Institute and offer them activities that interest and amuse them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to classes, we try to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the construction of the Jedlička Institute, we will transfer this project to a new independent building.
Several bands and performers will take the stage at each of these concerts?
According to what criteria, did you choose them?
We have tried to develop a program that caters to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform on stage.
You will find all the details on www.kpks.cz.
Are you also preparing for other "mega events" of this kind in the future?
In May, we will play for the first time as part of the Prague Spring; Here too, we will surely prepare a quality program with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year in the house of the Czech Republic in New York and personally, once there in the United States, I would like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is nevertheless a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not as bad as it looks at first.
We have five members in electric wheelchairs whose machines have to travel in the hold, naturally we also carry a lot of luggage and boxes of instruments....
So far everything has more or less always gone well, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Through your travels abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of access for people with reduced mobility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have witnessed in Moscow that in the East everything is still in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very inaccessible to people with disabilities; There, it is not yet common for a person to move alone in an electric wheelchair in the center of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association is being set up to draw attention to the problems of disabled people.
How do we still need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are many things for which we are still late...
It is important to mention that improvements and refinements always depend on the efforts of the people involved.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move around alone in public spaces; They can go to the bathroom, to the museum, anywhere...
It is not very common there that a large number of disabled people actively participate in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather at the forefront of progress!
Respect for the public and ease of access are one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have famous sportsmen, artists, actors, politicians or jurists among us.
At the moment, these are just isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, let's go back a few years, what prompted you in 1998 to create this group?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people ready to invest in something.
And since I am a musician myself (I play, among other things, the saxophone), with a colleague, we created a music activity.
And then, over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, we lost control of the situation a little bit (laughs).
Success has only happened in recent years, am I mistaken?
It's true, connecting with well-known singers and actively working to promote the band helped us.
We understood that, if a work is not visible, it is as if it does not exist in the background.
Thanks to subsidies from the European Union, we can also afford to have quality teachers, equipment, and so on.
Did you aim to reach such a level with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt there was potential to change things.
Show business is full of stuff that copies each other.
In a way, it makes sense: everything new is accepted with caution and it lasts a long time.
There are few original projects, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally pity, it is natural ...
But pity is totally useless, because people with disabilities are not suffering beings, abandoned by all, whom we must take pity.
These are people who can live a life in their own right and flourish, provided they have the necessary means of course.
I often say that when people with disabilities manage to achieve something, it is not only a step forward for them but for society as a whole.
Isn't your success also due to the fact that you are a demanding leader, as you are qualified by many people?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many areas and demand discipline.
But I think that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds, and when they realize that they have to come to rehearsals twice a week, take preparatory classes and spend a lot of time on the road for concerts, they quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But it works the same way in every group that wants to work and achieve goals.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them were already there in 1998?
Only one, Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, there is nothing we can do about it.
Our doors are always open to those who want or would like to join us.
