Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started working closely with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's journey to space, however, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flight; They did not always meet understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his pioneering work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his book " Introduction à l'astronautique ".
The said doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote numerous books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned propagator of astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
As early as 1925 a draisine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only known information about this draisine are those of the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to focus on rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the documents preserved that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war put an end to its activities.
After the war, further works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company was mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problem, which contained four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched, and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and by autumn the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were begun in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; They were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on public works.
This decision provoked a lively debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberalism-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
In practical terms, this means that the various economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This results from the principle of free trade and free (limitless) movement of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
Considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate pressure on prices.
The following meaning should be put under this term: a producer endeavours by importing low-priced goods to resist economic competition by "making the competitor's price more expensive", with the aim of taking away a larger share of the market and thus increasing his own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, buy cheaply, or disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries with high labour prices compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social charges of the State necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so common knowledge that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in different economies in which the governments of different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without regard for social collapse.
This is mainly manifested in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to force its own population economically to accept the price dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This occurs on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand by the restriction of employees' rights in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening differences between rich and poor.
In the FRG, there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of such people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay extra to reach the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal has come to light, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The cost-saving measures of virtually all the southern Member States of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live on poverty wages, on the margins of society,  in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
Here we must ask ourselves the following question: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or else a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media are tired of saying that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the command economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital fiercely defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and even direct today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same token, the entire state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is a practically all-powerful lobby present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that, due to lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the preparation of draft laws to law firms closely linked to industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalism-oriented democracies are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled ' The crisis of the Roman Empire in the time of Caesar and Pompey': ' The state had long been in disarray and functions were assigned by violence.
Bribes, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
Bribes and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold"... ... "Honest people did not seek to obtain functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls".... 'It really began to be said that the remedy for this difficult situation was autocracy and that an energetic man had to be chosen'. It is true that Appianos had Pompey in mind, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, today's society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
At its core, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result, today as in the past, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
As things stand, the disappearance of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and internally, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for ways to lower the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms that will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase citizens' influence on government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society to the benefit of the state.
