The movie Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist students stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
This was a blow to U.S. prestige, further compounded later by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their plight sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed heavily to Jimmy Carter's defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode in this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to incredible coverage: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who had come to scout for the shooting of a science fiction movie.
Combining genres
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is on the one hand a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a treachery - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres follow one another: documentary-style sequences of Tehran (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of the events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
and then scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions with men in costume discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting stopped eliciting ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark detective "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not set in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; The initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the word.
He does very well, he sometimes adds certain elements to reality and there, the result is not always so elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is removed by a phone call to America and the pursuit on the airstrip are quite far-fetched).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters would have deserved a greater place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with moderate interest, appreciating the filmmaking and retro style of the 70s.
He draws the viewer along, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the trick.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and the circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which conducts an annual public inquiry into the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the competition for the regulation or the most absurd ideas from the "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is considering, in recent times, adopting a quota of 40 percent of women for the management of large European companies was at the origin of our decision," the organizer of the survey, Patrik Nacher, told the newspaper Právo.
Among the absurdities mentioned, there is already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have had an advantage in life insurance rates because they objectively represent a lower risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible ideas from the "EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the obligation to add bio components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers solely because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of hens' cages, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticism has also been levelled in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the withdrawal from sale of conventional light bulbs.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (for example, the Czech Republic currently imposes the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto power).
The interests of pressure groups are also, for example, behind the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonising non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
Standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, claiming that existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year's EU regulation that airbags must include a warning that children under 8 should not inflate unsupervised by adults.
The EU referred to a US investigation that found that balloons are the leading cause of death of children from suffocation among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 from blowing fair trumpets.
At home, too, we have strange ideas.
The following rule regarding EU officials themselves is quite absurd: due to the sensitivity of this issue for Greece, anyone with an official function within the EU cannot use the name 'Macedonia' and must, instead, speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In cooperation with the association "Laissez Faire" of liberal economists, the Bankovnípoplatky.com server named in this survey, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the Union regulation on the volume of food reserves on the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food reserves that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, then exceeded the fixed volumes for canned mushrooms and thus risked a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found interesting the idea of paying sums of money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a subsidy to apply for subsidies.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"The fact that we don't have a sea handicaps us.
We will ask the European Union for a refund." So said the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
He argued that, because of our wheat production, and following the so-called "interventionist" purchases, the state had left itself with full stocks that it then had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech request and organized a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
The grants for obtaining subsidies were proposed to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development led by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), these were, concretely, to be used to draft applications for subsidies granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "bizarre regulations are rare".
While regulations are often criticised in the Member States, according to many experts, the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the Union's functioning and in the area of its overall development deserve praise.
More serious, for example, according to experts, is the problem of using EU subsidies for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States during the budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a struggle from which it does not always emerge victorious) arouses strong emotions among the Czechs.
If, after six years of battle against the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky", as for the name "Tuzemský rum" which dates back to the nineteenth century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák".
Only products based on cane sugar alcohol, and not based on beet sugar, may be called rum.
In the official list of registered EU products, together with world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, you can now find Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham, Karlovy Vary biscuits ("Karlovarské suchary"), Pohořelice and Třeboň carp ("Pohořelický a Třeboňský kapr") and Žatec hops ("Žatecký chmel").
Pardubice gingerbread ("Pardubický perník") and cakes called "Cornets de Hořice" ("hořické trubičky") can also be proud of their Community trademark.
