MVRDV's architects prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large company nearby, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed very beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one willingly goes to one of those cheesy libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that is not attractive on the outskirts of Rotterdam, holds a rather peculiar record.
The municipality of 80,000 people has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro notes in the form of pretty little miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
That's how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, a master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a sneer on his face.
And while the jury members were still looking at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the cheeky one, stacked his choice books in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by activist arguments with a: "dear commune!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and some buildings and terraced houses for a total of 50 homes.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was shortlisted for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is how this small dull village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of astonishing ugliness, whose white facades invite us to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lamps speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally, the library shelves are along the façade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We have completely changed the classic spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the book mountain has been skilfully laid out: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental center and the building technical center.
A particular beauty lies in the black shelves of the library, which are sometimes paneling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair railings.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don't want unfamiliar materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
For example, one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, the millimetre-thick synthetic membrane has been used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields for years.
It's cheap and time-saving.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons and then can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but above all they contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun illuminates the interior for a short time, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted askew from the glass façade serve as a sun visor, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as the "soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, during the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the gaps in the library, which was not yet fully stocked (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The shelves are overflowing on all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty bookcase."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this edifice.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page in literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request for observer state status at the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
What for?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has a special relationship with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Eventually, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy that is so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore came up against several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still groping to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean to the Germans in concrete terms?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, and therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and abstention in the UN vote?
Germany first has important outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Is Germany harming its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that the divide is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will be all the more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions about the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto in a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic political scene in the United States.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policies.
Is Germany having any difficulty in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things any easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today this is not the case.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must assert their singular position.
That is what they are doing now on the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will in future assume the role of locomotive and push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, not least because of its relations with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they have to play a role that marks their independence more.
Does Germany see itself playing a major role on the international stage, does Germany just want to play a key role?
Or does it still struggle to take on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to carry more weight, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with a wide variety of neighbours and opinions, and it's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European politics is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're even less appreciated, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyze the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... What is it really about?
Behind this name hides a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the undertaking bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, he is not sure she would win her case.
"It's becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in property infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new folder arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few more letters to be able to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, Lu-Gucci is recorded, and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is recorded.
German companies are also being copied legally, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sporting goods.
Pattloch opens a binder containing the registrations made with the Beijing trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell practically only counterfeits.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: his principals charge him with attacking the fact that the Chinese trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are designated.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to reproach themselves with.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," Pattloch said.
"The brand is watered down, the singularity disappears, the damage to the reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, China is the world's third fastest growing luxury goods market with an annual volume of €15 billion.
However, it is not easy to remove dubious registrations from the trademark registry and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch refers to the lawsuits in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period of time, the name criticized had become a "reality of the market".
Pattloch explains that if the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because he would have damaged his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
This is the reason why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, Volvo's owner, used to use a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW. The dispute was settled and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost to plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the famous crocodile's gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing, however, admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office reportedly went from an "emergency situation in the workflow to a restored normality" last year.
Thus, the number of opposition proceedings not dealt with would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases have reportedly been closed, representing a 75% increase over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the office.
Taking action is expensive
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and means that China is at the top of the ranking for the number of new filings worldwide for the tenth time in a row.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan in registration fees.
In other words, each registration brought in an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
Admittedly, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"It's our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany," says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trademark office had therefore rejected the objection of the Munich.
Freudenberg won his case in the next two instances, but the opposing party continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "The procedure is long, strenuous and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs. The archives even had to review the acts of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered the opposing party a "large six-figure sum in euros" to settle the dispute.
"That's what it means to us," Wentzler said.
The dangers of the Far East threaten even to spill over into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region ensured the exploitation of unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to register Freudenberg's name in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it had still been able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Vigilance is required."
He and Pattloch advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, they say, to rely on international trademark law, but rather "register in China everything that is likely to be protected," as Wentzler puts it.
Otherwise, the costs can be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of his own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
World AIDS Day: tapping, singing, helping
The Imbongi choir is rehearsing in Heidelberg, and AIDS orphans in Swaziland are looking forward to their visit.
This is the story of a link that spans much more than a distance of 8.733 kilometers.
First, we tap our feet: cowboy boots, sneakers, pumps for ladies and loafers for men seek rhythm by hitting the ground with their feet. Very quickly, they find it.
One, two, three, four.
Then, the voices of the singers are slowly amplified - alto, bass, tenor and soprano - they are carried away, bewitched and follow each other.
Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old conductor almost loses his canvas shoes when he conducts the orchestra with his wildly flexible gestures.
It's Monday night, the Imbongi choir is rehearsing a new song in the music room of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg.
Fifty singers from 23 to 69 years old came, from the geneticist in human medicine to the housewife.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each singer has different lyrics, all in a very exotic language: Zulu, a language spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
Be helped to help yourself
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS programme, estimates that 34 million people worldwide are living with the disease.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
Swaziland has 245,000 infected people.
In addition, more than 40% of the population is HIV-positive.
180 AIDS orphans from the village of Esitjeni have found sponsors in Germany thanks to the association "Voices for Africa".
70 of them attend secondary school.
For 15 or 20 euros less, you can become a sponsor.
This sum guarantees the child money for school, a school uniform and a daily hot meal at the gogo center.
Imbongi means in Zulu "storyteller" or "singer of praise".
No one can speak the Bantu language fluently in this region, but everyone can sing it.
For nearly 10 years, the choir has been rehearsing songs in this foreign language that it brought to Germany and now returns it to its native region: Southern Africa.
Because 8,733 kilometers as the crow flies from Heidelberg, in the northwest of the Kingdom of Swaziland, is Esitjeni, the village that depends on the vocal power of the German choir.
40% of people affected
The village has about 2,000 inhabitants, some live in modest huts of straw or earth and the majority of them are children.
More than 300 of them are orphans because HIV has taken their parents.
In Esitjeni, Swaziland's ills can be seen on a smaller scale: the highest HIV infection rate and the lowest life expectancy in the world according to UNICEF.
The population almost never accepts male circumcision, a measure that guarantees a proven reduction in the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of Swaziland's population carries the immunodeficiency virus and it is not uncommon to die in their mid-thirties.
During a group trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir was able to discover the village. The Imbongis especially saw many children on the street who lacked not only parental care, but also simply everything: food, clothing, education.
In a poor country, without a school diploma, there is simply no prospect.
In the beginning, it was just a few people who personally pledged to contribute a few euros each year so that they could send a child to school and offer him a hot meal a day.
But barely a year later, the choir founded "Voices for Africa", an association that has been caring for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni in an almost professional way ever since.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are primarily concerned?
Syphilis and gonorrhoea often appear in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is responsible for at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than among other population groups.
According to European records, three-quarters of all infections are among young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papillomavirus is common in young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years: from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been declining.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one-tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual disease?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white discharge, pain in the lower abdomen and the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms may decrease the risk of infection, but they do not provide 100% protection.
This is because pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricating infection or close bodily contact.
Experts therefore recommend that anyone who often changes sexual partners take regular exams.
Most STIs detected quickly can be cured and late sequelae can be prevented.
