A survey of a country in which people are still relatively young at 97.
The journey to the Talysh Mountains is a dishevelled romanticism.
At the bend of the many turns of the road, the small bus bumps along wooded hills, torrential rivers and modest farms.
Everything is green and fertile, it almost feels like the Black Forest.
But here we are in the deep south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
This is where the Caucasian ethnic group called Talysh lives, about whom little is known, except that they speak Persian and Azeri perfectly and have a very long life.
Terminus: Lerik.
The small town plasters with its overly aggressive Soviet-era architecture that doesn't fit at all with the picturesque mountain scenery.
European tourists are rare here, the journey from Azerbaijan's capital, Baku, is far too painful.
It takes eight hours to travel the 323 kilometers, as the road has only one lane.
The province has yet to benefit from the legendary wealth the country owes to its oil reserves in the Caspian Sea.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva, 48, is convinced that Lerik has the potential to become a tourist spot.
"Baku became famous in May thanks to the Eurovision Song Contest, and next year there will be the festival of the oldest people in the world here," Fatulayeva said.
She is director of the Museum of Longevity, the only museum of its kind in the world.
You can discover the life of about eight dozen Talysh of the region who are more than 100 years old. Fatulayeva shows us a black and white photo.
This is my grandfather, he has reached the age of 120.
Still having a child at 136
But the controversial star of the museum is Şirali Müslümov, a shepherd who is said to have been 168 years old.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And when you consider that the oldest documented person was 122 years old, Müslümov's age seems more than doubtful.
"He was born in 1805 in this region, he died in 1973," Fatulayeva said.
The man is said to have married three times and had 23 children. At the age of 136, he is said to have conceived a girl again.
Would Şirali Müslümov have been wrong by a few decades in calculating his age?
Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, also heard him talk about man in old age in Central Asia.
"Surprisingly elderly people also live in parts of China, in Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," Scholz explains, "in Sardinia too, there are men who live incredibly old."
However, it is impossible to establish scientific proof because of the non-existence of documents, not to mention that there was no civil registry.
Every day, a glass of melted butter
It is nevertheless a fact that the people of the Lerik region often reach an age worthy of the patriarchs of the Bible.
Currently, 20 people are over 100 years old.
So what is the reason for the longevity in the south of this country?
Farid Mugimzadeh, the Azeri tour guide, explains that the Talysh have particular genes.
On the other hand, Fatulayeva, the director of the museum, thinks it is a question of food.
However, it does not seem plausible, from a nutritional point of view, that the high-calorie meals of the Talysh, who love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of whom drink a glass of melted butter daily, are good for health.
Or is it the simple way of life that preserves people's youth? In Cengemiran, a tiny village near the town of Lerik, lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At 97 years old, she is still relatively young for the region.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a modest wooden house, as is typical to see throughout the Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor next to a churn, the contents of which she beats tirelessly.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and a daughter, who have long been adults.
Two small children also frolic in the house.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared for guests served in typical belly shaped armadus glasses.
Mirzayeva's white teeth are perfectly aligned, and under her scarf are hidden long braids of a dark blond that her son reveals with pride.
I always washed my hair with milk, and that's how I never lost it and it kept its color.
"I've never used shampoo," Mirzayeva adds.
Monthly retirement is enough to live on
She has always eaten what comes from her own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
In all my life, I have never bought a single food in a supermarket.
Then she tells us about her husband who was in the army.
The worst moments were after World War II.
But everything improved when the "beloved father" Heydar Aliyev took over.
The language of propaganda astonishes in the mouth of an old lady.
However, the cult of the father figure of the nation, a man who ruled his country like a dictator, knows almost no limits in Azerbaijan.
He was in power until 2003, after which was succeeded by his son Ilham.
In any case, the elderly of Azerbaijan do not experience distress.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manats a month (about the same amount as in euros) for her pension, a sum that guarantees a good lifestyle in the region.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's long-graying son is right: "elders enjoy great respect in our culture."
They are the center of the big family, they are loved, cared for and happy.
That's a good reason to live as long as possible.
