The rakfisk of Norway: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
Norway's five million people enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be related to the locals' appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty soccer clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's most popular delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It's snowing, the scenery is spectacular - and this smell, omnipresent, permeates the air.
Rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can be up to a year.
When darkness sets in and it's cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw, then you have a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter also known as "Rakfisk General," who is responsible for running the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk," Havard adds.
The drink kills the smell.
I try a few pieces.
If you can avoid running it under your nose, it's not bad – it's reminiscent of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, fish was immersed in airtight barrels of water and then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish is taken out and - undoubtedly with the senses diminished by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
Rakfisk is considered something important, a vital, albeit fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you €10 each.
Norway is not often talked about in international news, which is not to displease him.
Here, people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot dead 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they speak of the "July 22 incident".
The Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own could have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 70s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the only reason for our success," says Anna, our waitress, with blonde hair and piercing blue eyes, the image of Nordic well-being, with a tray of rakfisk in hand.
We are - how do you say - prudent people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth very carefully - everything except a small percentage of money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out the window in the years leading up to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep its purse strings tight.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"Not to mention rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and queue to buy food - I've had my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger composed of momentum, a real discovery, it's excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them – or perhaps the smelliest of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish, in the Thor-Juergen mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of aquavit abuse.
Or maybe it's because of fish fumes.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto had a rough start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, the BBC's Will Grant looks ahead and the expectations of the people, of which there are many.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are legion in normal times, a security roadblock has been in place since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the aim was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential sash to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico's economy is doing well, thanks to incumbent President Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already claimed the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
"My government is committed to the Mexican people to reduce violence," Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
