"I hope he will be as good as president as he was when he was governor," Olvera said in Congresswoman Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of mistreatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter allegations of abuse against Manning during detention.
The trial involves Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to dismiss the case on the grounds that Manning's confinement took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried Friday to demonstrate that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being behind the biggest leak of confidential information in U.S. military history -- missed numerous opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he claims he suffered while in military custody.
During cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months in detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be dismissed on the grounds that the forcible confinement took place under very difficult conditions and was a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide while in custody.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were later published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms the officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, while he was held in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein brought up the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received within the prison overall was "very professional."
The forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had verbally expressed concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the issues raised.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and that didn't mean I hadn't raised any issues," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special commission that met to discuss suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a "risk of injury."
The military said they assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know I was fine, and I wanted to be stripped of that status... in order to have a better quality of life from my perspective," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at Marine Corps Base Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he considered committing suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had were a mattress, blanket, flip-flops, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay moving, as sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned around at night, they woke him up so they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked overnight in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates one morning during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions Friday, Manning said he deduced from his guard's order that he had to drop his blanket that could have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to let go of it.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underpants or flip-flops to injure himself, but that he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences while in detention and significantly reduce his sentence if he were to be convicted by court martial, a trial expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the lesser offenses and fight for the dropping of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations that govern the conditions of detention of all detainees at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information relating to national defense.
If all charges are upheld, he faces life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He says many have been forced to leave Mexico because of lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says the Mexican-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby in front of customs and immigration, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two routes: one for the "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood still for several seconds, not knowing which line to head to.
I grew up in central California, where I've been called the "Mexican" all my life.
It's an ethnic adjective, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves "Irish," or my friends in New York when they call themselves "Italian."
Then I became "Mexican-American".
But, here, it was Mexico.
And, on the land where my grandfather was born, there is no need for a special qualifier or hyphen.
I was simply an American.
I speak Spanish, well enough to handle an interview in either language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and headed to the "Foreigners" line.
I thought about that time of the week when Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited President Obama in the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their favorite themes are immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risk the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada, and create a Union for trade on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, though he did not provide further details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and filled with bitterness.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory in writing at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, not minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear -- in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how the Americans are infringing on the sovereignty of their neighbor.
And Montezuma's children are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans who live in the United States.
Do you want us to talk about bitterness?
There are a lot of them.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not.
The only reason that explains the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at some point in our family tree, a person, perhaps a parent or grandparent, did not find any opportunity in Mexico and had to go north.
And more often than not, that person fit a typical profile -- dark, poorly educated, poor village skin, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we are currently living the American dream, we have gone to good schools and we have good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that this is the American dream we are living, not the Mexicans' dream.
Our identity is sometimes troubled, but our loyalty is obvious.
We give it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they toast us as if we were individuals of inferior and not sufficiently Mexican stock.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we wouldn't find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but as lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally emigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because Mexicans claim their identity more firmly and Mexican-Americans are upset about it.
Although she is a U.S. citizen, she feels part of two countries.
On the other hand, many Mexican Americans I know don't feel like they're part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and part of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as ambassadors of fortune for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our fellow Americans that Mexico is a beautiful country that must be visited and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes of course.
That will not happen.
There is too much bitterness.
And, considering the pervasive wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're going to have to fend for yourself, amigos.
This is normal.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way it treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexican-Americans still resent them for the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we are more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old quarrels, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Can there never be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such hope is vain.
While the same futile arguments persist as to who started it, dozens of buildings have been reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza landed near Tel Aviv, Israel's metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring shattered everything, and like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
