Plain cigarette packaging laws have come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of diseased organs cover the dark green packets that are all the same, regardless of the brand
This law that came into force in Australia is a world first, the logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrific photos of diseased organs and depictions of children and babies whose illnesses were caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the various photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all the packages.
It is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government has said the aim is to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous portrayal.
Studies have shown that if people didn't start smoking until the age of 26, there's a 99% chance they'll never start.
"Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco companies through their branding," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that found, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess.
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry lobbied against this law.
Tobacco companies said this would revive the black market trade, which will give easier access to cheaper cigarettes.
"There will be adverse consequences from this legislation," said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters in China and Indonesia will sell many more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said the law had boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned business, said demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to hide horrific packaging, has risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in Australia's High Court.
Ha said Zico has sold 6,000 to wholesalers and is waiting to renew its stock.
For us, business is good.
The only problem, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the segment of population targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws banning TV advertising, sports sponsorship and requiring retailers to conceal cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
Australia has banned web advertising by local companies and sites, but it cannot stop foreign sites from doing so.
"If you work in tobacco marketing and you only have a small storefront to promote your products, the internet is the place to be," said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman has noticed an increase in contributions from some ordinary citizens to brands on social media like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
We have to ask ourselves, is this a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes and has gone to the trouble of making a video, or is it a marketing campaign orchestrated by an agency?
British American Tobacco Australia said the industry is focusing on the new regulations in place rather than marketing.
The industry has gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge these new court rulings – these countries have told the WHO that trade is unfairly disadvantaged, although none of these countries have had significant trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in the course of 2013.
Plibersek said the government had held discussions with other countries regarding similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to mandate photo warnings on packaging in 2001.
At present, these warnings are present in 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are currently under consideration in England, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia remain unmoved by these photos.
The photos don't bother me.
I do not know them.
