The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After going through numerous publications and submitting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of "wanting to do something, but failing to engage in a satisfying activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although they would like to.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do something.
What is at the heart of boredom, he said, is "the interruption of the attention process, coupled with a sullen mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
Boredom can strongly resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while the two can be linked, bored people tend to think the problem is with the environment or the world, while depressed people think the problem is with them.
Sometimes we think that we are bored when it is actually a problem of concentration.
As part of their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," which was published in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an earlier experiment in which participants listened on cassette to the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard the loud sound of an unrelated TV show from the next room, others just heard the TV show, and the third group didn't hear the soundtrack at all.
Those who heard TV at a low noise level said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but didn't know why, and attributed this concentration problem to boredom.
When you're trying to focus on a difficult or time-consuming task, an interruption in attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
