So we thought: what could be more creative to solve this problem than to make it a rap song?
1.2 children
The Singapore government does not take it so lightly.
It spends US$1,300 a year on policies to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this had little effect.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its rulers' conservatism and strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, in line with its national population distribution, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policies of the National Population Division, says this is due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities."
"This has given people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and forming a family," she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of single people and delays in marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in Singapore's birth rate.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to counter the decline in population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound with thinly disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially the Chinese who are accused of dragging down wages and not integrating.
Increased immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party had its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the election, they have tried to correct the problem with the implementation of quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unintended consequences
While falling birth rates have known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also has unintended consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoeboxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate company EL Developers, says his "shoeboxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these homes are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put in the works if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations could be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed, houses are expensive, and so is education, that's why people put it off," says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it's important to have my money and time," says another twenty-something.
Both men and women cite their careers, the stress and cost of home ownership and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the final say.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of privacy that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is private for children under 16?
How to apply this definition in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposing himself to by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, who are frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level with "password and username" when applying it to social networks.
"I won't reveal my most personal secrets in a post," says ten-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the meaning of the term private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mother may know them but not everyone," he said.
On FB, I post cool pictures or games.
I also chat with my friends.
"I won't share one of my photos or someone who would be a fool," he says.
The young boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, nude people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine followers on Twitter.
The majority are family.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just post them," he adds.
"Social media is fun, I can talk with distant relatives or friends, fast," he says.
He says he would never accept an unknown person's request.
Nor will he trust someone who would recommend a stranger to him.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not knowing 20 of the people on his friends list.
"It doesn't worry me because we have something in common, music for example," he says.
According to the young boy, no one made advances to him or asked for his address or phone number.
"If they pressured me or demanded it, I would just remove them from my account," he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A relative of one of my friends was racketed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He only passed it in private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a safe way.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or upset.
"Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he said.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, considers that, to guide children and adolescents, we must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a way to search for information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras points out that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants," uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are they, children and young people who are born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them, while we ourselves are learning," she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what should or should not be disclosed, published or said at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so".
"We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," she adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach privacy to children and adolescents is to use questions that make them think.
"There's no point in telling them not to," she said.
Then Porras lists some examples: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a picture of you like a friend you posted?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you tag photos of parties, do you ask other people for permission to tag them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you're doing at every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they must act online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social networks," she said.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, a university teacher, primary school teacher and education adviser, says it is essential for parents to read the terms of use of social media conscientiously.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid foundation to discuss with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
"For example, age and what is allowed to share or publish," he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The Unasur summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration having been made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe tried several times to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Unasur Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially signalled that it would be released after the summit closed, then claimed that it would be published any moment on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been consistently limited.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
What little information circulated among the journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, the presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although it was urged by the press, it had not issued the declaration also known as the Lima Declaration, as had previously been announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, we can verify that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the access to information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the arguments of both sides in the lawsuit Lima has filed against Santiago that begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing today before this international court," Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals," President Piñera added, shaking hands with President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered gravely erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The trustee read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, access to low-cost Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to glimpse a better future for our populations," concluded President Humala.
"We decided to focus on a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Of these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the cross-cutting axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the outcome document refers to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will require a discussion with this country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they are scheduled to witness the takeover of that country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc's defense ministers will meet beforehand to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the presidency pro tempore of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship," says Rafael Correa.
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa said today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal for which "South America, in this case, must follow Europe's example."
President Correa, who participated in the VI summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), located in Lima, told state television, TV Peru, that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are almost a homeland."
In this sense, he defended the project to establish a South American citizenship encouraged by the member countries of Unasur.
"We must achieve the free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already the case for the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary areas that we want to make a thing of the past," he warned.
In addition, the Ecuadorian President has shown himself in favor of the reconstitution of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of reducing the influence of Anglo-Saxon States and taking into account the signatories of the San José Pact on Human Rights.
Those who beat our ears never compromise anything, conversely, we South Americans have all signed it.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under US funding," he said, referring to Ecuador's political asylum for WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assures that he does not regret his decision, because he himself did not betray his principles, but on the contrary he respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He concluded that at the time, "there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his trial would not be respected."
In addition, he criticises the Swedish judiciary for requiring him to submit to an interrogation on its territory concerning an alleged sexual offence whereas "Sweden's own legislation allows this to be done by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa claimed there was a risk that Assange's mental and physical health could deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he's been in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has a small lung problem, but nothing serious," the Ecuadorian president said.
Their physical and mental health may deteriorate by being locked in a small space without being able to exercise in the open.
"It affects anyone's health," he concludes.
Correa points out that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, which would be the granting of a safe conduct that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and European judicial authorities and he points out that he has had discussions in London in order to find a solution to the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
We are not negotiating with human rights, we are not using that word in this case, but there have been ongoing discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a whole series of proceedings before different European bodies," he said.
And he thinks that "if Britain granted safe conduct tomorrow, it would end".
And if Sweden, as its legislation fully allows, and as it has already done in other cases, were to question Mr. Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or to question him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate was "mediocrity, bad faith and lies that harm freedom of expression."
"The biggest enemies of press freedom are not malicious or evil politicians but bad journalists in the pay of greed, blackmail and extortion," he said.
From this perspective, he welcomed the fact that it was not this kind of journalist "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador" and, rather than putting forward his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution to continue the path and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay within Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the body "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts," because in reality "it destroys the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy."
Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considers "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime limits between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court in The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
For the moment, this judgment is not respected.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
They must be resolved as a whole in order to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the successful resolution of the maritime boundary dispute between Peru and Chile in the same court and affirmed that it is "beneficial for Latin America to seize international bodies if both countries agree to accept a judgment however firm it may be".
Referring to the possibility of his candidacy as a candidate in the future presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he said he saw this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that, if he lost the February 2013 primaries, he would retire from public life.
On a personal level, power has never interested me, but in situations as unjust as those in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this eventual victory, but we must accept this responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last presidential term and I would then retire from politics.
If we ever lose, I will too.
"It's my decision," he said.
Correa also referred to Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez's new medical treatment in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse in President Chávez's health," he said.
The Ecuadorian Head of State participated today in Lima in the VI Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which ended with a call for better regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths today are due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed the test result: HIV-positive.
"It's as if the sky has fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", to no avail.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take charge of his illness on his own and began to learn about it and his relentlessness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the longest-serving patients in the HIV unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), where he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 90s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless".
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and fall victim to opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG,  Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as a reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious disease specialist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system damage that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs:  up to age 30 for a CD4 count of 200 and up to age 50 for those with a CD4 count of 500.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who receives a positive HIV diagnosis at age 25, "as long as they remain under control, will be able to live without problems until age 75," explained the scientist interviewed.
In order to put this progress in context, it should be noted that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who have died from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the emergence of AIDS, 60% of the patients recorded on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths up to May this year; However, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I think the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we have never run out of drugs, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
He gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, we must offer screening tests massively, to all people who request it".
Specialists and members of the Jalisco State Council for AIDS Prevention (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to be tested in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma,  a cancerous tumour that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you find out you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better that I have fun three times a week," they say, this is not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, through his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Whether they get tested, if they have taken risks, the sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programmes and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packs of a hundred, which is very good, but the result is that even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among those most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that adolescents do not want to hear, assures the journalist.
It proposes to redirect this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but that they be found in public washroom vending machines and in places frequented by young people.
It is not a question of encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González replied when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
"That's not how sexuality works, it's best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active," he said.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is the 4th state in the country in terms of new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th in terms of HIV patients.
92% of infections are sexual, 6% bloodstream and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for every recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who do not know it.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt agreed to through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario sets a bad precedent for all national companies with branches in neighbouring countries and solvency problems.
It seems that the corporate survival procedures allowed by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star-spangled banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the June 15 judgment of Bankruptcy Court Judge Harlin Hale for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's largest glass manufacturer to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge in the case noted that creditors must register under U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, stated that the main proceeding was commercial bankruptcy formalized in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing cross-border procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a cross-border profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Trade Law had been created for that purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Second, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognized in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries to the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, the case of Vitro is not the first to use this plan.
There are half a dozen examples here, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since there were still the votes of the subsidiaries, in any case the creditors of Vitro who fought against this in the courts of the United States, that is to say the "vulture" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
Data omitted by the appeal court.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation he had been facing since 2008 without stopping at the severe economic crisis facing the United States, passing on the costs to the country.
For now, the González Sada family company will appeal to the same appeals court to have the vote taken place in its entirety, i.e. with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance lawsuit will claim non-prosperity and require a review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the U.S. Supreme Court of Justice.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") detailing the procedure followed by Vitro under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, pointing out that this freed him from the agreements signed by the two countries to bring it on the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States bankruptcy law.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules laid down for cross-border insolvencies, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Pile-up of two parts: they knock out Vitro and they knock out the country.
