Basketball globetrotter "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the court and, thanks to him, has traveled all over the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much knowledge of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a cerebral hemorrhage condemned him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower-league player, a player on the national basketball team, a manager and executive of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several hats in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 90s," Reyes recalled during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel.  his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes is not exaggerating when he makes this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia reminiscent of his extraordinary itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves the most are those that remind him of his time as a player with the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after spending 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships starting in 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or executive.
That's been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, 'Cuco' Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a manager here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a strong player for you, he is two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
That's how Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had, began.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had helped Bayamon win a championship, Gausse was going to help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only from a distance since in 1988 he was already the big man of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his responsibilities and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 Worlds, where we came 4th and we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us replay the last game," said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've seen?
She is one of the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat up the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the youngsters (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the León brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the 90 World Cup because of a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level as Piculín did.
And this without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It is very difficult to say.
We had a good team consisting of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work that Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest achievement within the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What is left for you to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as regionalizing minor categories.
For example, the boys of Ponce only play in their zone and only play against teams from other corners of the island in the national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when it is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff, and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
I usually listen to music, watch clips from my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, formidable and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the TV series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night from complications of cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production company of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his press secretary, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an exceptional person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumour and underwent a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas," Hagman had made a name for himself on television as an ordinary guy in the NBC series "Jinny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two comedies that remained on the air for a short time, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include critically acclaimed roles in "The Group," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", coined to maintain suspense around an emotional episode in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars gambled in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers were in front of their screens and made "Dallas" the second most-watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which garnered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had impregnated her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave town, but other people also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R.," Hagman said in 1988.
One should write: "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing".
Here's the only game he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, recalled this Friday Hagman as a man "immense, both on the small screen and in life".
He is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes has already been completed for the second season and a sixth is in the works, the channel informed.
For now, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated on how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who rose to fame with classic works like "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan."
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He made his debut on the stages of New York theaters in the early 1950s and then served in the air force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
"I didn't write anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told reporters at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist worried patients.
"I advise them, I give them confidence, I come with them when they come for surgery and after," he said in 1996.
I try to offer them some comfort, like, "Don't be afraid, it won't be easy for a little while, but it's going to be okay."
He has also been an anti-tobacco activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hook: the end of the "great countdown" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, which many people refer to as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what lay ahead in the coming months: the catastrophic Sandy hurricane, a fiscal sinkhole that some have dubbed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end-time theorists thought the apocalypse would unfold.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever had," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only professor to give lectures on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze movies with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacer said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to teach a course, simply titled "The End of the World."
"We are adding '2012' to have the opportunity to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't disappear," Professor Restall said.
Despite the "impending disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was sold out in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-level students, which consists of 35 students.
We received email messages several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, says he's watched all the apocalyptic movies.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone one professor, told us they believed in the December 21 end of the world.
"Our first project dealt with the Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it," says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old senior Temple student from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it's only a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an apocalypse anxiety in Western culture, dating back centuries, that makes people react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge in these speculations.
"In other parts of the world, people don't think about that," he said.
Most of this is the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religion professor at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew "the end of the world" was taught here.
"The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years there has been talk of the many supposed dates of the Last Judgment, and he claims that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and professors take the date lightly.
Several told us they were thinking of going to "end-of-the-world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh about it together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
